Introduction

This exercise gets at an important issue in classification, namely severe class imbalance. The actual remedies for this are not dealt with until Chapter 16, so this data allows us to explore the potential issues this causes in terms of creating samples, dealing with rare classes and choosing a data splitting strategy. Exercise 4.4 has already dealt with creating samples and using stratification to ensure that the samples are representative and that rare classes are included. Therefore in this exercise I will look at data splitting and implementing a model. In the original paper, Brodnjak-Vonina et al. (2005)1, the authors train models on the data we have available in this exercise. They also apply the model to a separate test set and make predictions. I have extracted that test data from the paper and also applied my model to it. My training and test results are similar to the authors.

Exercise Instructions

Instructions adapted from Kuhn and Johnson (2013)2.

In Exercise 4.4, we described a data set which contained 96 oil samples each from one of seven types of oils (pumpkin, sunflower, peanut, olive, soybean, rapeseed, and corn). Gas chromatography was performed on each sample and the percentage of each type of 7 fatty acids was determined. We would like to use these data to build a model that predicts the type of oil based on a sample’s fatty acid percentages.

  1. Like the hepatic injury data, these data suffer from extreme imbalance. Given this imbalance, should the data be split into training and test sets?
  2. Which classification statistic would you choose to optimize for this exercise and why?

(a)

Based on the data it seems that leave-one-out cross-validation (LOOCV) would be the best option here. This way each class will be represented in each resample. The rarest class is G, but there are two observations with class G which means that even if one class G observation is chosen to be left out there will still be one observation to be trained on. Computation time is typically an issue with LOOCV, but the data set is small (\(n = 96\), \(p = 7\)) so it shouldn’t be an issue here.

NOTE: tidymodels does have a method for splitting data for LOOCV (rsample::loo_cv()), however the various functions for fitting models do not actually implement LOOCV. It is computationally expensive and it may not have good statistical properties and so it hasn’t been prioritized for implementation3. Therefore I have manually implemented LOOCV using a mixture of tidymodels objects and regular R code. I have chosen to implement just one model for now, namely linear discriminant analysis (LDA). The LDA model can be used for multi-class problems and can be used to make a prediction on one observation at a time (multinomial logistic regression seems to have issues in this regard). Also, Brodnjak-Vonina et al. (2005) use LDA and LOOCV to establish a baseline, so I can compare my results to theirs.

(b)

Since this is a multi-class problem and there is a large class imbalance, the accuracy rate alone may not be ideal. This is because simply predicting the most popular classes is likely to get a good result. Cohen’s Kappa takes into account the class distributions of the training samples and the accuracy that would be generated simply by chance. I will calculate the accuracy rate and Kappa for this exercise.

Modeling

Here I will implement LDA with LOOCV. For preprocessing, I will use step_corr(), which as we saw above will remove one predictor from the data.

# Preprocessing
rec1 <-   
  recipe(y ~ ., data = df1) %>% 
  step_corr(all_predictors(), threshold = 0.9)

# Model
lda_mod <-
  discrim_linear() %>% 
  set_mode("classification") %>% 
  set_engine("MASS")

# Workflow
workflow <- 
  workflow() %>% 
  add_model(spec = lda_mod) %>% 
  add_recipe(rec1)

# LOOCV
n <- nrow(df1)
preds <- c("")

for(i in 1:n) {
  fit1 <- 
    workflow %>% 
    fit(data = df1[-i, ])
  
  # Trace:
  if(i %% 10 == 0) 
    print(paste0("Holding out observation no. ", i, " of ", n, "..."))
  
  preds[[i]] <- predict(fit1, new_data = df1[i, ]) %>% 
                  pluck(".pred_class") %>% 
                  as.character()
}

The Kappa value is 0.9445.

It turns out that the accuracy (95.83%) is actually a good measure of performance because the model has not got stuck on predicting the most common classes. Rather it has predicted 92/96 held out observations correctly. It even correctly identified the two class G observations.

It also turns out that 92 observations correctly predicted is exactly the result the authors of the original paper got with LDA and LOOCV. The only difference is that I get a percentage of 92/96 = 95.83% while they report 92/95 = 96.84%. The exercise mentions that the authors of the paper seem to have miscounted the number of samples as the exercise also reports 96 training samples. See below where I read in the data from the original paper and count the unknown and known samples. In the paper, the observation that is incorrectly included in the unknown samples is the one with ID of 27. This is actually given a class of 2 by the paper authors in their own table 1.

See below for a quick comparison between my results and the paper where I perform PCA, and also compare predictions on the unknown samples by my LDA and the authors’ neural network model.

Original article

In Brodnjak-Vonina et al. (2005), the authors use LDA and LOOCV on the training data (\(n = 96\)) to establish a baseline accuracy rate which they report at 96.84%. They also train a counterpropagation neural network in the same manner and report accuracy of 98.95%. This neural network is then applied to an unlabeled test set (\(n = 37\)) and probabilities are obtained. As the data is unlabeled, it’s not possible to directly asses the quality of the predictions. However, the authors compare the model predictions to the manufacturer’s description of each oil and find they correlate well.

In this section of the notebook I recreate some of the graphs and tables from the paper. Ultimately I use my LDA model to make predictions on the test data and compare the results to the authors’. All but two of predictions were in agreement.

Filter out the unknown samples and create a test set: (the one with ID of 27 is included in the paper’s unknown samples but it actually has a class of 2 according to Table 1)

df2_test <- df2 %>% 
  filter(class == 0) # a class of 0 indicates an unknown sample
df2_test

# First retrain the model on ALL of the training data:

    workflow %>% # workflow and associated recipe already defined above

preds2 <- predict(fit2, new_data = df2_test) %>% 
            pluck(".pred_class") %>%

Conclusions

This exercise provided an imbalanced data set with some rare classes. This makes it difficult to apply standard data splitting approaches. Later chapters deal with more advanced methods to remedy the class imbalance, but this exercise is a chance to explore using leave-one-out cross-validation (LOOCV). This method is typically not preferred over other methods, but the small sample size means the computation time wasn’t prohibitive. I implemented a simple linear model (LDA) and was able to achieve very high accuracy on the training data. In particular the model was able to correctly predict the two samples from the rarest class during the LOOCV process. I also applied the model to a test set and was able to achieve comparable results to the more complex neural network model used by the authors of the original paper.

Future work

It may be worth implementing some more linear and non-linear models on the data. This might require implementing a tuning method if I want to tune over a grid of parameters. However there is limited data and the LDA model used in this notebook achieved a high accuracy. Also, the LOOCV approach seems to be less useful in general so it may not be much help to have a working implementation.
